{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516617"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12671"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12671"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.77,0.03,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5147"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106373"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5147"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12671"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88836"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43344"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44827"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106373"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old female visited her physician complaining of a rash on her cheeks and nose, aggravating when exposed to sun light, painless ulcers in her mouth, severe hair fall and pain in small joints of her hands not associated with morning stiffness. She also complains of fatigue and decreased appetite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is a rash on bilateral cheeks sparing nasolabial folds, non-scarring alopecia and tender small joints of the hands not associated with any deformity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"which one of the following has high specificity for the condition mentioned above?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti nucleolar antibody (ANA)","Anti ds DNA antibody","Anti Ro antibody","Anti La antibody","Complement levels  C3 C4"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture in the above scenario is consistent with Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE). It is an autoimmune disorder with\u00a0multisystem involvement.\u00a0More than 90% of cases of SLE occur in women, frequently starting at childbearing age. Clinical characteristics can range from a very minor illness with only mucocutaneous involvement to a serious, multiorgan-threatening illness. In SLE, any internal system may be affected. Sometimes, an autoantibody profile can be used to forecast the course of a disease and its clinical manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-nuclear antibody ANA,\u003C/strong\u003E is a screening test, it is sensitive but not specific for SLE. A positive ANA with negative testing for more specific autoantibody testing is less likely to be associated with systemic autoimmune disease.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-double-stranded deoxyribonucleic acid (dsDNA) antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E have more than 95% specificity for SLE, it is both specific and sensitive for SLE\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-Ro and Anti-La antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are specific for Sjogren syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplements C3 and C4\u003C/strong\u003E shall be checked in patients with SLE or suspicion of SLE. In active disease, complement proteins are consumed leading to low complement levels, therefore the levels are checked to correlate with the disease activity. Moreover, the presence of congenital deficiencies of complement (especially C2 and C4) is associated with an increased risk of developing SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore it is neither sensitive nor specific for the diagnosis of the disease\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Systemic lupus sclerosis, SLE, is an autoimmune disorder, multisystem inflammation, more common in females. It is characterized by the involvement of musculoskeletal, renal, dermatologic, neuropsychiatric, pulmonary, gastrointestinal, cardiac, hematologic systems.","Positive anti dsDNA is highly specific for SLE."],"references":["Justiz Vaillant AA, Goyal A, Varacallo M. Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. [Updated 2023 Aug 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535405/","Infantino M, Nagy E, Bizzaro N, Fischer K, Bossuyt X, Damoiseaux J. Anti-dsDNA antibodies in the classification criteria of systemic lupus erythematosus. J Transl Autoimmun. 2021 Dec 28;5:100139. doi: 10.1016/j.jtauto.2021.100139. PMID: 35028552; PMCID: PMC8741517. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35028552/","Almeida Gonz\u00e1lez D, Roces Varela A, Marcelino Rodr\u00edguez I, Gonz\u00e1lez Vera A, Delgado S\u00e1nchez M, Aznar Esquivel A, Casa\u00f1as Rodr\u00edguez C, Cabrera de Le\u00f3n A. Anti-dsDNA antibodies in systemic lupus erythematosus: A combination of two quantitative methods and the ANA pattern is the most efficient strategy of detection. J Immunol Methods. 2015 Dec;427:30-5. doi: 10.1016/j.jim.2015.09.003. Epub 2015 Sep 25. PMID: 26407840. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26407840/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88836"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12671"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88836"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T11:06:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T11:07:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5147"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106373"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":n